# 🔹 Recursion Tree Method

Used to solve recurrence relations by expanding them level by level.

---

## Example 1

[
T(n)=2T(n/2)+n
]

### Level 0

Cost:

[
n
]

### Level 1

Two subproblems:

[
2\times\frac{n}{2}=n
]

### Level 2

Four subproblems:

[
4\times\frac{n}{4}=n
]

Every level contributes **n**.

Number of levels:

[
\log_2 n
]

Total Cost:

[
n+n+n+\cdots (\log n\text{ times})
]

Answer:

[
O(n\log n)
]

📌 Classic GATE question.

---

# 🔹 Example 2

Solve:

[
T(n)=T(n/2)+1
]

Each level contributes:

[
1
]

Levels:

[
\log n
]

Answer:

[
O(\log n)
]

---

# 🔹 Example 3

Solve:

[
T(n)=T(n-1)+1
]

Expansion:

```text
T(n)
=T(n−1)+1
=T(n−2)+2
=T(n−3)+3
...
=T(1)+(n−1)
```

Answer:

[
O(n)
]

---

# 🔹 Substitution Method

Guess the answer and prove it using mathematical induction.

Example:

Guess:

[
T(n)=2T(n/2)+n=O(n\log n)
]

Substitute into the recurrence and verify.

📌 Used when Master Theorem cannot be applied directly.

---

# 🔹 When Master Theorem Cannot Be Used

Master Theorem **cannot** be applied if the recurrence is not of the form:

[
T(n)=aT(n/b)+f(n)
]

Example:

[
T(n)=T(n-1)+n
]

Use:

* Expansion
* Recursion Tree
* Substitution

---

# 🔹 Comparison of Methods

| Method         | Best Used For            |
| -------------- | ------------------------ |
| Expansion      | Simple recurrences       |
| Recursion Tree | Cost per level           |
| Master Theorem | Standard D&C recurrences |
| Substitution   | Complex recurrences      |

---

# 🔹 Common GATE Traps

### Trap 1

Quick Sort worst case:

[
O(n^2)
]

NOT

[
O(n\log n)
]

---

### Trap 2

Merge Sort worst case is always:

[
O(n\log n)
]

---

### Trap 3

Binary Search recurrence:

[
T(n)=T(n/2)+1
]

NOT

[
2T(n/2)+1
]

---

### Trap 4

Master Theorem cannot solve every recurrence.

